{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_grackle_ver01/data/sn84020107/0051701476A/1913082501/1045.xml":{"full_text":"IK BEATRICE DAILY EXPRESS\nPublished every evening except Sunday\nIt 121-123 South Fifth street by the\nktinuci bxpbxss m. oo.\nFrank o. Edgecombe President\nH. W. Munson .Sec'y and Mgr,\nvs. THR DAILY EXPRESS.\nBy mall, one year .$3.0(1\nBY matt, one month .25\nBy carriers In city, per week.10\nHew Bell Phone Bumber \u00bb337.\nBorne Phone Bnmber\u201414.\nAny subscriber falling to receive The\nExpress regularly and promptly should\nnotify this office at once, either by\nphone or In person.\nb. c. ramenra. editor.\nSKXSEIjKSS optimism.\n'The recent drought in Nebraska\nnod other states has called forth a\nlot of senseless optimism on the pait\nOf'Bome newspapers, public speakers\nadvertising men, etc.\nBy senseless optimism wo moan\nbroadcast, sweeping statement of\nprosperity, of resources unimpaired,\nof Rood business in spite of curtailed\nC^ops, and a lot of other generalities\nthat have no definite meaning or\nany real foundation.\nThat sort of optimism does very\nlittle good, In fact a sensible pessi\nmism is sometimes preferable ns it\ndoes not bring out false hopes and\ngets business men into a frame of\nrtllnd to meet the situation.\nAs a matter of fact the general\nbusiness outlook for this section\ndoes give ample foundation for op\ntimism, but not for the grand, glor\nious circus advertising optimism that\nWo fee occasionally. The drought\nhas hurt and It Is well to admit it.\nhut In admitting it It is better to get\najt the real facts, size the situation\nuji as it really Is and then prepare\naccordingly.\nThero Is no occasion for the busi\nness men of the middle west to bo\npessimists, or to view seasons just\nahead with uneasy forebodings, for\nthe facts do not warrant any sucii\ngloomy view. On the other hand\nthe man who allows himself to be\nblinded to real conditions by sensa\n]es soptimlsm will go as far astray\nand miss the mark just as wide as\nhe who Is too pessimistic.\n....Trade Exhibit has endeavored to\navoid either extreme, and especially\nthat of too much optimism. We have\nmade diligont inquiry among the.\nbusiness men of this section to get\na real line of the business outlook\nand we think we can sensibly and\nSafely predict that things might be\na great deal worse, and that on the\nwhole the prospects tor business this\n411 and winter,- taking the whole\nterritory into consideration, are as\ngood as last year.\u2014Omaha Trade\nExhibit.\ni The fact that Great Britain,\nPrance, Japan and j radically all of i\nthe Central and South American\ncountries arc lending their support\nto the American policy with Mexico,'\nis causing a great deal of uneasiness\nand anxiety In the Huerta regime.\nUnless satisfactory overtures are\nmade by the Huerta government by\nTuesday President Wilson will pro\nclaim in person In a message to\ncongress the principle that constitu\ntional government alone can be\nrecognized In Mexico.\n'\u25a0Once wo had the privilege of lis-j\ntoning to a short sermon by Edward\nEverett Hale and the beat point he\nmade was the admonition to touch I\nShoulder to shouldrr with the rank\nand file of the people In your com-1\nmunlty. It Is not necessary to en\nlarge on that tersely stated advice j\n6r\u2019to point out Its advantages for\ntlig retail merchant.\u2014Trade Exhibit.\n'S* There is a sentiment taking form\n>h Washington that all lobbyists\nmust wear a badge on his coat lapol\nto distinguish him from members of\nCongress. The badge might also\nplay an Important part in getting\nrecognition of the members by the\nlobbyist who is known to have a full\npocket.\n\"Thaw aces nothing to worry\n\u2022bout,\" says a headline in the dai\nlies. Thaw's line of vision has un\ndoubtedly been Impaired by his in\ncarceration. Most auy ordinary man\nwould worry his head off if caught\nU) the same situation that Thaw now\n(fecuples.\n,^1 Is ap 111 wind that blows nobody\ngood. One merchant is quoted as\nsaying that the dry \u201dwea\u201cth\"or is go\nCASTOR IA\nTha Kind Ycu Han Always Bought\nv1.\nr\nFor Infants and Children.\n\u2022denature of\nBears the\nHow We Are Illogical\nBy RUTH CAMERON\nTHK facility will) which the average mortal blames other people or\nfate for hi* own mistakes and failures Is very wonderful to con\ntemplate.\nBut not any more wonderful than the avidity with which the same\nmortal accepts credit and praise for his own successes and triumphs, no\nmatter how large a share other peo >le and fate may have had in bring\ning them about.\n1 have a friend who Is an inveterate match-maker.\nNot long ago one of the matchei at which she assisted resulted in a\nmiserable divorce suit and we all wondered if she\nblamed herself fo.- the unhappy outcome. Not at all.\n\"I can\u2019t tell you how sorry 1 am for poOr Margaret,\nand for Roger, too,\u201d she assured the: \"I wish 1 had\nnever thrown then together, but of course 1 don\u2019t\nblame myself at all. How could I know that they\nwere going to make such a mess or it? Margaret has\nbeen very cool to mo ever since tltey began to have\ntrouble with each other, but I\u2019m sure I don\u2019t see why\nshe should be. If she didn't know that Roger wasn\u2019t\nthe right man for her, she certainly couldn\u2019t expect\nme to.\u201d\nPerhaps you will agree with the unfortunate\nmatch-maker and think she could not be blamed for\nher failure. So should I if It were not for this\u2014she won\u2019t take blame\n:or the failure of her efforts but she will take credit for their success^\nAnother couple whom she pushes in o matrimony have heen consplcu\n)usly happy, and instead of admittln; it was juBt a happy chance she is\nIways congratulating herself on her foresight in selecting these two for\nach other, or complaining because the wife has not shown sufficient\ngratitude.\n\"It\u2019s a pleasure to see anyone *.s happy as Eva and her husband,\"\niho says, must say I\u2019m proud of that match. 1 said from the very first\nday I saw them together that they were Just the ones for each other, and\nI can\u2019t tell you all I did to bring it about. Eva admitted at the time\nthat she would never have married him if it hadn\u2019t been for me, but she\nseems to have forgotten all about that now.\u201d\nAgain you may say that you think the match-maker deserves grati\ntude for bringing about a happy match, and again 1 admit she does, if\nonly she will accept blame for the unhappy ones.\nBut if she will not accept blame for guessing wrong the first time,\nche ought not to ask praise for guessing right the second time.\nIf we are going to set up an abstract fate on which we can blame all\nour mistakes, logic forces us to give it the credit when we guess right.\nBut the human race is notriously illogical and, as 1 said before, the\nfacility with which we shift the blame for our mistakes ts only equalled\nby the avidity with which we demand the credit for our successes.\ning to sell more fanned goods for\nhim this fall and winter. There's a\nsilver lining to the darkest cloud,\nfor somebody.\nWe are inclined to view with sus\npicion tlio news that a fisherman in\nCalifornia landed a 335 pound sword\nfish with a pole and line the other\nday.\ni Beatrice in the Past jj\nFrom Files of Dally Eipress\nt in 111.1 li.i eii eii dui. iid eiiwiinm-iMr'rt<i* it i>i i in huuhbS\nTuPIve Years Ago.\nThe thermometer registered 10o In\nthe shade down town.\nMrs. H. It. Studley of North Loup\nwas visiting her son, Dr. L. W. Stud\nley.\nMias Jessie McGee of Blalrsvlllo,\nPa., was the guest of her uncle, J. L.\nMcGee.\nMrs. W. B. Knouse was visiting\nfriends In Liberty.\nat\nTwenty-one Years Ago.\nMilo Savage was home, from Des\nMoines where he had secured a Job\nas contractor at a paving brick fac\ntory.\nMrs. Enri l.ongtin and children had\ngone to Monteno, 111., for a visit if\nfour or five weeks with her mother.\nCarson V. Cole had returned from\na three months' trip through Scot\nland, England, Fanee and Bermany.\nMrs. M. Callely came home from a\ntwo weeks\u2019 outing at Manitou.\nMrs. Wm. A. Wolfe returned from\nSalt Lake City, where she had been\nvisiting for the past six weeks.\nTwenty-live Years Ago.\nR. J. Kilpatrick left for a business\ntrip to Denver.\nThe Beatrice Board of Trade ac\ncepted an invitation to attend the big\nbridge celebration at Nebraska City,\nAug. 30.\nA daughter was born to Dr. and\nMrs. A. N. Pierce.\nProf. J. P. Vance, musical director\nof Centenary M. E. church, was elect\ned to a chair fct Nebraska Wesleyan\nuntvojrslty, to act as professdr of\nmusic.\nDenver. Aug. 23.\u2014New ideas in\nlandscape gardening were exchanged\ntoday at the opening sessions of the\nthree day\u2019B convention of the Amer\nican Association of Park Superinten\ndents here. It is the fiftieth annual\nmeeting of the organization. The\nmen who are responsible for most of\nthe beautiful park systems of the\nJ United States are 'n attendance. J.\n|S. Macbeth, president of the Denver\nDark Board, welcomed the delegates.\nOne of the principal features of the\nconvention will be an automobile\ntrip through the chain of mountain\nparka recently established by the\nCity of Denver.\nCOMMUNICATED.\n\n\nj A friend from Edgemont who was\na visitor at Hot Springs last Thurs\nday, informs me that K. B. Kinback\nformerly quite well known in Beat\nrice, is in such delicate health that\nI he is unable tg leave the house to go\nI down town.\nComrade Wheaton of ward C made\nme a friendly visit on Thursday last\nand on the same day drew his govern\nment clothes, got his red pass, and is\nnow a full fledged member of the\nsanitarium. He is looking fine and\ngetting better every day. I think he\nhas just found the place and climate,\nfor I never saw any one change so\nmuch in so short a time. On the\nother hand comrades under the same\nconditions go down. In some cases\nthe physicians say the altitude is too\nhigh and recommend a lower one.\nRoger Evans who has been making\nHot Springs his home for some two\nmonths, has gone to Oelrichs, pre\nsumably to visit his brother David\nand look after his claim in that vicin\nity.\nWhile we have bpen receiving news\ndaily of the sweltering condition of\nthe atmosphere about Beatrice we\nhave been congratulating ourselves\non the favorable conditions prevail-\ning in South Dakota for showers hav<\nbeen so frequent that if it should be\na little warm some afternoons the\nshowers follow and make the air\npure and delightful,\ni Congressman and Mrs. E. W. Mar-;\ntin returned last week from Wash\nington, D. C., and the first of the fol\nlowing week came down from Dead-1\nwood In their car and are spending\nthe week at their ranch north of Hot\nSprings. Congressman Martin has a\nbill before congress to give all South\nDakota Homesteaders an additional\nquarter section. He has douht about\ngetting the bill through at this extra\nsession of congress but says it will go\nthrough at the regular session next\nwinter.\nKeverting again to weather condi\ntions, late news from friends at Spo\nkane, Wash., conveys the information\nthat they bad gone to a lake up in\nthe mountains, fishing, and the cold\nwas so severe that they were compell\ned to return home again, but said the\nfishing was just fine.\nSince I have been sending commun\nications to the Express 1 have some\ntimes wondered whether the material\n1 send is of sufficient interest to jour\nreaders to justify their continuance.\nIn a letter recently sent me from a\nBeatrice comrade he assures me that\nthey are gratifying to the members of\nthe post and corps. If such is the\ncase I am perfectly willing to con\ntribute them.\nJ. G. CARNAHAN\nAug. 22, 1913 Ward 1. B. M. S.\nsinus\n\nBut With the Assistance of Cap\nsized Boat He Won\nthe Girl.\nBy LOU 18 OLNEY.\nWhen he called for Patricia some\n,-thlng in her face told her that hei\n\u2022time of reckoning had come. Vani\n(Harris was the sort that will be dan\ngled Just about so long, but no longer\nand she knew that even for her sh<\ncarried matters with a high hand. Sh<\njcarefully began by extolling the per\n.fectly worthy weather. Patricia hat\n\u2022instincts.\n\"The lake is lovely, isn't it?\" sht\n\u25a0remarked as- they strolled to the litth\ndock, \"smooth and clear, and it's noi\n(too warm. A canoe is just right to\n.day.\" She looked at him sidewise\u2014\nhis dark face was a bit grim, bui\n\u2022he smiled.\nHe knew that Lawrence Patterson\nthe only rival he really feared, hac\nJust returned from the west and wat\nat this moment searching for Patricia\n\u201cYes,\u201d he conceded, the \u201ccanoe, the\nLake, the day\u2014and you\u2014seemed the\nright combination. That\u2019s why\nwickedly cut commuting to the office\nand came for you. It\u2019s luck to have\nfound you.\" She also gave a little\ngrin. She had come partly to suil\nherself, partly because she had latelj\ntormented him as far as she dared\nbut mostly to discipline. Ted Barnard\n\u2022who was becoming too importunate\nand whom she had left on the veran\nda unconsoled by her younger sister.\n\u201cWe must be back early,\u201d she in\nfbrmed him, \"I am due at Mrs. Forbes\nfor luncheon. There is a new man\u2014\nshe won\u2019t say who. I am supposed\nto make things interesting for the\nnewcomer.\u201d\nVane silently helped her to hei\niiioii Bum ittiuig uer, luumii\nfashion, with his one paddle. He was\ntall and well-knit, bareheaded with\nthe wind blowing bis heavy, dark\nhair. He looked fondly at Patricia,\nin her cream flannels, her hair a glory\nin the morning sun.\n\"I guess you know how to make\nthings interesting for a man\u2014when\nvou choose,\u201d he answered, b\\lt with\nout malice. \"I should know that.\u201d\n\"What do you mean\u2019\u201d she queried.\n'Experience teaches,\u2019 he said, at\nlength, \u201cthat Miss Patricia Carey\nsomehow makes a ma.i aware of her\npresence. When are you going to\nmarry me?\u201d He demanded abruptly.\nH- had never before asked her out\nright. Now his tone didn't suit her.\n\u2018\u2018I don't fancy the threat In your\nvoice. I haven\u2019t said that I would\nmarry you at all.\u201d She trailed one\nhand In the water, carefully looking\naway from him. All at once he\nstopped paddling.\n\"The threat,\u201d he spoke drily, \"is\nintentional. You have trailed me, a\nmore or less, willing victim, .for a\nyear now. At first I was not sure\nthat I\u2014wanted you.\u201d She gasped at\nhis impudent frankness. \"The reason\nwhy I thought I might not want you\n.was that you have never lived in a\nreal home. When I marry I want a\nwoman who will make a real home.\nI can give her everything a man can\ngive toward making one. I mean\nthat your people died and left you\nand, you poor little thing, you have\nbeen passed about from aunt to aunt\nand badly spoiled. Don\u2019t be angry\u2014\njust hear me out. But I began to see\nthat your instincts are true and fine\nand right, and that all you needed\nwas a chance. You are very domestic,\nbut you don't know it yet.\u201d\n\u201cThank you.\u2019 she interrupted, her\neyes wide with angry astonishment,\nand an angrier consciousness that he\nwas speaking the truth. He went\nquietly ahead with his personal re\ncording of fact.\n\u201cI decided that in San Francisco aft\ner I had known you three months.\nFor the six months thereafter, by let\nter when not in person, I endeavored\nto make you love me. I came to my\nown conclusions, which were\u2014that\nyou either loved me or you didn't,\nand that in either case you were a\nperfectly skilful coquette. So the last'\nthree months I have rather rested\non my oars to see how far you would\nlead on Ted Barnard, and a half\ndozen Others none of whom you care\na rap for!\u201d\n\u201cIn-deed!\u201d She ejaculated, while he\ntook the paddle again and turned the\nboat so that the sun would be out of\nhis eyes and full in hers, not a gal\nlant proceeding, but useful in his\nstudy of her eloquent little counten\nance. \u201cYou are quite clairvoyant.\"\nOnly\u2014observant\u2014ana reflective,\nPatricia. No other man\u2014except Law\nrence Patterson\u2014has really troubled\nme for a moment. Do you care for\nhim?\u201d\nShe looked her scorn of the ques\ntion. \"When he asks me that, I shall\ndo as I like about answering. As for\nyou\u20141 don\u2019t think I care much about\nthis trip with you. I didn't come out\nto be bullied. You may take me back.\nAunt Margaret is quite right\u2014I should\nbe more careful and not go about un\nchaperoned. She will be back in a\nfew days now\u2014\"\n\"She will be back tomorrow,\u201d he\nsaid quietly. \u201cI was talking with\nMiss Clayton this morning\u2014you know\nthe society editor on the Tribune?\nShe gave me the glad news. Don't\nknow how she knew. Hut, to get down\nto business, when are you going to\nmarry me? I withdraw the question\nabout Patterson. It is too late now\nfor you to\u2014consider him.\"\n\u201cVane Ketterling Harris, you can\nbegin paddling back for the dock!\nYou must be insane! What ails\nyou?\u201d\nTib not going to paddle back\u2014and\nI shall recite a little history for yout\nI benefit. For nine months, either in\nI person, or by letter, I nave kept aftei\nyou, and you have encouraged me\nbeautifully without in words commit\nting yourself. You have gone every\nwhere with me, I have carried you\nover rough places, literally as well\nfiguratively. You have, on rare occa\nsions, let me kiss you. You have,\n;wlth your sweetness and dearness,\n[coaxed the heart out of me. It is in\nfyour keeping, and I demand an ac\ncounting. I don\u2019t know any way but\n(this to get a positive answer. We are\n|a long way from shore, the water is\n,deep, and you can\u2019t swim, a fact ol\n'which you should be ashamed, since\nl have offered to teach you. You\nShouldn't allow yourself to be afraid\njof water\u2014you know that.\" He turned\nand scanned the lake. \"Now,\u201d he went\n.on, \u201cwe will have to have things out\n'with each other. You have never let\n\u25a0me openly ask you to marry me. You\nhave interrupted, fled, Joked, torment\ned, all because you feared that being\nengaged would cut short some ol\nyour flirtations. Which is perfectly\ntrue. My fiancee can\u2019t jooquette with\nevery man in sight, she will have to\n.behave.\u201d He put on his cap and\nwent to work again with the paddle,\ntalking as he did so.\n\u201cBriefly, you mary me or you don\u2019t,\nand you decide now. Uncle Martin of\nfers me a partnership In his Denver\nbusiness, a sure thing and a money\nmaker, and I am to let him know to\nnight what I will do. If I take It 1\nshall leave Immediately for Colorado.\nIf I don\u2019t, I shall go on with my pres\nent work, which I like best. But\nyour preference would decide me.\nThis is why it is up to you. What are\nyou going to do with me?\u201d\nShe gave him a look of utter scorn.\n\"Do you think you can\u2014bully me?''\nshe inquired. \u201cDid you think this\ncould make me\u2014love you?\u201d\nHe smiled. \"No\u2014If I didn't happen\nto know that you love me. If I didn\u2019t\nKnow now you love to dangle and tor\nment a man I would never have tried\nIt. But you do love me\u2014only you\nhate to give In and admit It, and I\nshall not take you back to shore un\ntil you do\u2014I have lunch In this box,\nand we stay here until midnight\u2014or\nmorning, unless you\u2014\u201d\nHer blue eyes widened and flashed\nand without a second\u2019s hesitation she\ngave a vicious little leap and over\nturned the canoe in mid-lake.\nJust as Vane Harris went over he\nhad the presence of mind to give a\nmighty shout for help. Two men not\nfar behind them came at their best\nspeed. Vane had gone down and\ncome up coolly, made a grab for\nPatricia and with her was holding to\nthe overturned canoe. Bawrence Pat\nterson and another man paddled\nalongside, but just as they began\nrighting the overturned craft and\nhad a safe hold on the girl. Vane\ngave a convulsel gasp, struggled, and\nsuddenly sank like lead. He did not\ncome up again. At first Patricia did\nnot realize the truth, then she gave a\ntittle cry, god they pulled Jier to\nsafety.\nThere was some shouting for help\nand In a minute a half dozen boats,\nsome swimmers, boys and men, were\non the scene There were directions,\ndivings, fears\u2014and finally the young\n.mans\u2019 limp body was fished up,\nhauled into a boat and hurried to the\nnearest shore. He was rubbed, water\nwas emptied out of him, air was\nforced into him, he was blanket\nwrapped. manipulated. Patricia\ncould not be coaxed or forced away.\nShe stood by, ash-white, hugging about\nher dripping figure a big blue cloak.\nFinally Vane gave a deep, gasping\nbreath, choked, breathed again\u2014and\nopened his eyes. Patricia put her\nhands to her face and wept. Mrs.\nForbes led her away, bundled her\ninto her car, and took her home. She\nput her to bed and began ministering\nto her. The luncheon was forgotten.\n\"You poor dear,\u201d she comforted.\n\u201cAnd on the very day your engage\nment is announced. You naughty girl,\nto let your friends see it first in the\nTribune! Of course we all knew you\nwould marry him\u2014but I couldn\u2019t be\nlieve my eyes this morning, so 1\ncalled up Miss Clayton. She said\nVane himself had asked her to print\nthe announcement. How lovely of\nyour Aunt Margaret to be your spon\nsor.\u201d\nPatricia hid her face on the pillow.'\nSo that was what he had done! He\nhad heralded her consent before she\nhad given it! Well\u2014hadn\u2019t she tor\nmented, trailed\u2014and finally nearly\nkilled him? Suppose he had drowned?.\nShe shuddered. He should have\ntilings his own way. She knew now\nwhat life might have been without\nhim. She turned a tear-wet but hap\npy face to her friend.\n\"Mrs. Forbes, will you go and see\nhow\u2014Vane is? Tell him as soon as\nhe is able\u2014I\u2014want him\u2014to come. I\nwant to see him.\u201d\nThe older woman bent over her a\nmoment, and then tiptoed away to do\nher bidding.\n'Copyright. 1913, by the McClure Newspa\nper Syndicate.)\nMedicinal Vegetables.\nLettuce has a soothing effect on the\nnervee and is excellent for sufferers\nfrom insomnia.\nTomatoes are good' for a torpid\nliver. but should be avoided by gouty\npeople.\nCelery and onions are nerve tonic.\nSpinach has great asperient quali\nties and is better than medicine for\nconstipation\nBeets are fattening and are good for\npeople who want to put on flesh. So\nare potatoes.\nParsnips possess the same virtues\nas sarsaparilla.\nAsparagus stimulates the kidneys.\nBananas are beneficial to sufferers\nfrom chest complaints\n.President Wilson to Personally Read\nMessage to Congress Tuesday\nat 1 O\u2019clock. o\n(By United Press.)\nWashington, Aug. 25.\u2014President\nWilson announced today that he had\ndecided to read his special message\non the Mexican situation before a\njoint session of the house and sen\nate at 1 o\u2019clock tomorrow unlesB un\nforeseen developments occur at Mex\nico City. A complete change of\nfront on the part of President Huer\nta is the only thing that will delay\nthe message.\nThe situation in regard to Mexio\nis as follows: The message of about\n4,500 words is completed. Presi\ndent Wilson asked for a conference\n|With the members of the senate and\n,house foreign relations committees\ni tonight to consider the message. The\nmediation proposal is included in\nthe message, also Huerta\u2019s note -of\nrejection.\nForeign nations are bringing pres\nsure to bear through their ministers\nat Mexico City to get President Hu\nerta to accept the United States\u2019 pro\nposal. No ultimatum has been giv\nen Mexico nor will any be given.\njThe United States will not reply to\nHuerta\u2019s note and an opening of the\nsubject will come from Huerta. Gov\nernor Lind may remain in Mexico\nfor some time or may be recalled at\nany minute.\ni The president's message is couch\ned in very friendly terms and em\nphasizes this country\u2019s friendship\nfor Mexico, although it feels that\nMexico\u2019s affairs are being misman\naged.\nWashington, Aug. 25.\u2014Great Bri-w\ntain, France and Japan are among\nthe nations which have interposed\ntheir influence upon the Huerta adr\nministration in Mexico in support of\nthe efforts of the United States to\nbring about a peaceful settlement of\nthe revolution.\nWhile administration officials\nwere silent today regarding this\nphase of the situation, there was a\nlively interest manifest in diplomat\nic circles here as to the probable ef\nfect of foreign pressure on the Hu\nerta government.\nIt was learned that the Mexican j\nauthorities hoped President Wilson\nwould not read his message to con\ngress next Tuesday as he had plan\nned and showed a disposition to pro\nlong the negotiations.\nUnless some tangible overture,\nhowever, is received withiu forty\neight hours from the Huerta officials\nindicating a desire to accept the\nfundamental proposals of the United\nStates the president will proclaim to\ncongress and the world the attitude\nof this government toward the sou\nthern republic.\nThe fact that diplomats from soms^\nof the very countries which not only\nhave formally recognized Huerta\nbut whose bankers hitherto have\nfloated loans for him, are using their\ninfluence on the Mexican administra\ntion is calculated to produce some\nthing definite shortly. Officials\u2019 re\nports to the state department show\nthe Huerta regime to be in desperate\nfinancial straits with little prospect\nof getting funds anywhere to meet\nthe running expenses of the govern\nment or pay it3 troops, already rest\nive because of deferred payments.\nSo important is this aspect of the\nsituation regarded that an air of\ntense expectancy prevailed tonight\nin official circles where it was be\nlieved some pronouncement would\nbe forthcoming from Mexico City be\nfore President Wilson finally deter\nmined to communicate his message\nto congreSB.\nH. W. AHLQUIST\nFARM LOANS BONDS\nREAL ESTATE INSURANCE\nOffice German Nat\u2019l Bank Bldg.\n\nW. 8. BOURNE\nAttorney at La*\nProbate Law and Settlement\not Estates a Special^-.\nOffice over Omaha Store.\n\nCHICHESTERSPILLS\n\n1\nf \u00bb\u00ab\u00ab\u00bbk\"\u00b0*n\u201cii\u00ab>-s.(t1.t.jiii;\u201e,R^.b\u00bb\nS010 BY DRUGGISTS EVERYWHERE\n*\u00a3B\n\n_ i. Mcoctu* r\nBy\u00ae, Bar, Nose and Throat.\nto 1* m.. J: SO to\n\u201cv 8und*y* by appoint-\n*Bank\u00b0Blk* 8\u201ctetaB N*tl0>'","height":"26312","width":"17048"}}
